My benchmark for all things bbq is the Salt Lick just outside of Austin, TX. so I have pretty high standards when it comes to my grilled/smoked meats. ÊI try to judge Chicago bbq by a different standard as it is a different beast and my personal opinion is that you can't really call it bbq if it's made north of the Mason Dixon line. ÊThen I ate at Smoque... Smoque can hold their own with the best of them, and I'm not talking Chicago bbq standards. ÊThese people are making bbq RIGHT, Mason Dixon line be damned. ÊThe very best ribs I've ever had in Chicago and, in fact, some of the best I've had anywhere, period. ÊI got the combo baby back/St. Louis and, although both were excellent, definitely favor the St. Louis style. The brisket...oh...perfect pink smoke ring, gorgeous bark, tender juicy meat. ÊThere isn't a brisket in town that can top it. ÊThe Texas Link IS a Texas Link. ÊHoly moly, I thought I was at some German smokehouse in Texas when I ate that thing - beautifully marbled with fat, smokey, juicy, and a natural casing that gives it a fantastic snap. I'm a happy girl. Sides are also good, I particularly recommend the baked beans which are studded with chunks of porky goodness. ÊMy husband hated the mac and cheese, I loved it. ÊIn fact, I loved it even more on the 2nd day, it's good stuff. ÊThe coleslaw is of the vinegar/pepper based school, not my fave, but has very finely shaved bits of red onion in it that really makes it shine. ÊIn fact, the only thing I've had here that could even be qualified as a disappointment is the pulled pork. ÊDelicious, but not nearly as good as the rest of their menu. ÊThat fantastic smokey flavor you find in all of their other offerings is lost on this dish. ÊIt's still tender and good, just lacking a bit of oomph/flavor. ÊIt is the one item here that I actually needed to put sauce on. The sauce, btw, is fantastic, but I definitely prefer the lighter Carolina based one. ÊMy one quibble is the lack of white bread - god intended us