Holy Smoque! After yet another fine meal at Smoque, I had to do it some justice and give back by writing a stellar review. Summary: It is a BYOB that serves BBQ - that's it! They don't have burgers, chicken wings, gyros, or hot dogs, because that is not what they do. I am tired of reading reviews that complain about not having a steak or a burger on the menu. Its a BBQ joint, not a steak house...get over it! Anyway, back to the topic I love and know well...BBQ! Smoque caters to the traditional BBQ lover. It has pulled pork, brisket, ribs (baby back and St. Louis style), hot links, chicken, and a few simple sides that are all outstanding. ÊBased on what type of meat you order, they have a sauce type that is specific to each meat. While you can stray from this sauce, you should give it a try as it was specially designed to compliment the meat (not over power it). They cook and base their sauce on the geographic region that is most well known for the meat: Pulled Pork - Carolinas Brisket and Hot Links - Texas Ribs - St. Louis and Memphis They have done their home work because I have eaten at some of the best BBQ joints in all of those regions and can say that Smoque does a good, if not better, job than some of the best BBQ joints in that area. The best tell tale sign of a good BBQ is if the meat can stand alone and not require sauce. Well, I have to say, Smoque's meat stands on its own like a new graduate from the Marines. It has an outstanding rub and is smoked to perfection. The portions are very reasonable as is the price. And if you can't make up your mind on what to order, you can add a "taste" of any of their meats for a small charge. Food: Pulled Pork - Great! As with all of their meats, it is available as a sandwich or a platter. It is tender, smokey, and has a good mixture of juicy center pork with the crunchier, spice rubbed outer part of the shoulder. Classic pulled pork with a thin vinegar based sauce which compliments the meat well. Brisket - Smoque's most famous item and what they do best. The brisket beats almost all of the Texas BBQ places I have been to. It is available sliced or chopped. The sliced brisket is juicier and so excellent. The chopped brisket is from the end of the brisket and is much leaner and probably my favorite thing on the menu. The sauce is a thicker sauce that is pretty tangy and should be used sparingly. Ribs - The ribs are amazing. They offer both St. Louis style and Baby Back style ribs. The baby backs are a little smaller, leaner, and a tad bit more money, while the St. Louis ribs are a little larger. St. Louis ribs get a bad rap for being fatty, but not at Smoque. They are pre-trimmed and are almost as lean, if not leaner, as the Baby Backs. In fact, if you ask the owners, they will probably steer you to try the St. Louis ribs. I always order the St. Louis ribs unless they are out of them. They are meatier, tastier, and just great. The ribs are not the typical boiled/broiled Chicago style ribs that my Gramma can eat without her dentures. Rather, they have a little "tug" to them, as Smoque puts it, and a great texture; the way ribs ought to be. The outer part of the rib has a really nice crust to it from the rub and the smoking process. The ribs are one item I never use sauce for...I always eat them dry. If you prefer the sauce, it is a thicker tomato based sauce and is somewhat of a hybrid of Memphis style and Kansas City style. It is pretty tasty, but as I mentioned, good ribs don't need sauce. Chicken - Well, its chicken and tastes like chicken. Decent, but not great. Why go to a BBQ joint to get chicken with all of the other options. Pass on the chix and go with the beef or pork items. Sausages/Hot Links - These were ok. I am not a huge fan of sausage, but they really didn't impress me at all. They really tasted very simple. ÊSee above regarding the my recommendation on the chicken. ÊIf you are a big sausage fan, then you might enjoy them. Beans - To die for! ÊThey are so good! Smoque takes pieces of chopped brisket and onion and adds them to the beans. They then smoke the beans in the smoker to perfection. I have never had BBQ beans as good as these. Hands down! They definitely aren't your standard Bush beans from the can. This is the best side dish on the menu, in my opinion. Mac and Cheese - Well done indeed. They use fresh cheese and hand make it. They top it with bread crumbs and toast the top of it. I am not a huge Mac and Cheese guy, but if you are, this one will be a hit with you. Fries: Hand cut fries that are decent. ÊUnless you have to have fries, consider other options. Sauce: Overall, I will say the sauce is good. ÊNot the best I have had, but it does its job. Finally: Ê If you haven't already, check these guys out. They are the real deal and have great food. If you don't believe me, check out their BBQ Manifesto on their website. They did their research and really know BBQ!
