s the sauce. ÊIt's cute how the sauce was served on the side as if it may ruin the majesty of the rub that was used. ÊPerhaps the reason is that the sauce was so...bad. ÊIt was definitely better than Open Pit, but not as good as Sweet Baby Ray's, which is available on the shelf at Dominick's. Ê Still I was certain the brisket would save me. ÊWrong! ÊSince when is brisket dry? ÊThis is actually the worse brisket I've had. ÊI gave it to my cat but she wouldn't eat it. ÊHowever, if you like Smoque's brisket, know that the $3 taste portion is a generous amount. ÊThe fries were excellent! ÊI haven't tried the pulled pork yet, but fear it may end up in the trash to keep the scrawny ribs company. Ê Sadly, Smoque was just another place in a long disappointing line that proves that Northside restaurateurs should just put away the sauce, turn off the smoker and travel a few miles to the South side to learn something about the food they are mocking with their below par efforts. ÊIf they don't want to go to the South side, then maybe a weekend trip to Jim and Nicks in Birmingham, Dinosaur in New York, Gates in Kansas or the guy with the BBQ grill in the post office parking lot in Waterloo, Iowa may help out. ÊThese ribs are all different, but they are all good. ÊJust please, I beg of you...go learn something so I can get good ribs close to home!!! Still there is one meaty reason for Smoque and their ilk to ignore my review and my advice... they have great reviews and tons of customers. ÊThis leads me to acknowledge that there is an entirely different way of preparing BBQ ribs which a whoooooole lot of people love and appreciate...the Northside way. ÊTo everyone who enjoys Smoque and their buddies - enjoy! ÊEat it up! ÊSop it up! ÊLove it! ÊI truly envy you in your bliss. ÊWhatever you do, do NOT go to the Southside and eat real BBQ, such as at Lem's on 75th, as you will find yourself in my position...forced to drive 18 miles for enjoyable BBQ ribs. If anyone reading this knows 